Final Answer:

Here is a curated list of 5 grant opportunities for biochemists researching cancer biology:

1. American Cancer Society Research Scholar Grant
   - Funding organization: American Cancer Society
   - Funding amount: $800,000 over 4 years
   - Eligibility: Independent investigators at any career stage
   - Application information: https://www.cancer.org/research/we-fund-cancer-research/apply-research-grant.html
   - Deadline: June 1, 2025

2. BCAN Career Development Award
   - Funding organization: Bladder Cancer Advocacy Network (BCAN)
   - Funding amount: $250,000 over 3 years
   - Eligibility: Junior investigators within 7 years of first faculty appointment
   - Application information: https://www.bcan.org/research/career-development-award/
   - Deadline: October 11, 2024

3. Victoria's Secret Global Fund for Women's Cancer Career Development Awards
   - Funding organization: Victoria's Secret, in partnership with Pelotonia and AACR
   - Funding amount: $206,000 over 2 years
   - Eligibility: Female early-stage investigators researching breast and gynecologic cancers
   - Application information: https://www.aacr.org/grants/victorias-secret-global-fund-for-womens-cancers-career-development-awards/
   - Deadline: May 15, 2025

4. Hirshberg Foundation Seed Grant Program
   - Funding organization: Hirshberg Foundation for Pancreatic Cancer Research
   - Funding amount: $75,000 for 1 year
   - Eligibility: Academic researchers, including research-track and clinical-track faculty, staff scientists, and post-doctoral trainees
   - Application information: https://pancreatic.org/research/seed-grant-program/
   - Deadline: August 30, 2024

5. Lung Cancer Research Foundation (LCRF) Research Grant
   - Funding organization: Lung Cancer Research Foundation
   - Funding amount: Varies (part of $3.55 million total funding)
   - Eligibility: Varies by specific grant type
   - Application information: https://www.lungcancerresearchfoundation.org/research/funding-opportunities/
   - Deadline: Check website for specific deadlines (2024 cycle recently closed)

These grants offer diverse opportunities for biochemists studying cancer biology, ranging from early-career development to established investigator support across various cancer types.

